aned up?"},    {"who": "Abraham Kimmelmann", "start": "9309.756","u": "Yes, after the room was cleaned up. But imagine yourself, we had no good brooms, we had to find brooms ourselves; gather weeds in fields and make brooms of them. We had no allotment of brooms. It was impossible; it just doesn&#39;t fit together. It was like this. The first days we were trying to do everything possible; crawl under the beds and look for a piece of straw. Then we got accustomed, one says, &#34;Well, let them beat me,&#34; but one can&#39;t anymore, one doesn&#39;t have the strength [to clean up]; can&#39;t anymore; &#34;I will get the beating but I am tired from work; I can&#39;t anymore.&#34; They would come in, two, three of them, and of course they would not look under every bed; they had no time for that; each one had to keep clean under his own bed. They would take a kind of sample and some nights they would not come in, but the fear was every night. I tell you every night until1&#226;2 o&#39;clock I could not sleep until I got accustomed to it, always looking for straw."},    {"who": "David Boder", "start": "9372.325","u": "Looking for straw during the night?"},    {"who": "Abraham Kimmelmann", "start": "9376.689","u": "Yes, during the night. As I have told you before, if one tuns around a piece of straw falls down. That&#39;s how it was. When one would go to bed, he would look below to see whether by lying down I [he] didn&#39;t in any way dirty up or that a piece of straw hasn&#39;t fallen down. They came in the first night; we were still new; what cleanliness is concerned they didn&#39;t find anything special; they didn&#39;t find anything, we took care of it; then they took up something else; that one had&#226;some had dirty feet, so they immediately beat up the room trusty that he had to be taken to the Revier [hospital] and everyone of us got twenty-five."},    {"who": "David Boder", "start": "9417.054","u": "What do you mean, everyone?"},    {"who": "Abraham Kimmelmann